# ✅ What Is a Refresh Token?

A **refresh token** is a **long‑lived credential** used to get a **new access token** **without forcing the user to log in again**.

### Token Types

| Token             | Lifetime         | Purpose                      |
| ----------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------------- |
| **Access Token**  | Short (5–15 min) | Used for API calls           |
| **Refresh Token** | Long (7–30 days) | Used to get new access token |

✅ If access token expires → use refresh token → get new access token  
✅ User stays logged in even after refresh / new tab / page reload

***

# ✅ Why Access Tokens Must Be Short‑Lived

*   If an access token is **stolen**
*   Short expiry **limits damage**
*   Refresh token is **more protected**

✅ This is **security best practice**

***

# ✅ Recommended Architecture (BEST PRACTICE)

    Access Token  → stored in memory (JS state)
    Refresh Token → HTTP‑Only cookie

✅ Access token → Authorization headers  
✅ Refresh token → never accessible by JS (XSS safe)

***

# ✅ Full Flow Diagram

    User logs in
       ↓
    Server issues:
       - Access token (15 min)
       - Refresh token (30 days, cookie)

    Client uses access token
       ↓
    Access token expires
       ↓
    Client calls /refresh
       ↓
    New access token issued
       ↓
    Continue without logout

